"# Chapter 3 — Matrices and matrix-vector multiplication

A matrix is a grid of numbers. Or: a stack of vectors. Or: a function
that turns one vector into another vector by a bunch of dot products.
Those are three views of the same thing. In this chapter you learn to
switch between them.

The matrix-vector multiplication is the operation of every
fully-connected layer in every neural network. Everything else in
the network is either applying that operation, or preparing tensors
for it. This chapter is load-bearing.

## What Motoi gives you

Motoi's `matrix/` verbs treat a matrix as a list of rows, each row a
list of numbers. `matrix/make` takes the list-of-lists and returns
a matrix; `matrix/multiply` multiplies two matrices; `matrix/transpose`
swaps rows and columns. For matrix-vector we will use the row-view
directly, which lets us see the dot-product structure clearly.

## Problem 1 — Build a matrix, ask its shape

```
(define M
  (matrix/make (list (list 1 2 3)
                     (list 4 5 6))))

(display (matrix/rows M))
;; => 2

(display (matrix/cols M))
;; => 3
```

Two rows, three columns. This is a 2×3 matrix. In print, the shape
is written `(2, 3)`. In tensor talk, its rank is 2 and its shape list
is `(2 3)`.

## Problem 2 — Multiply a matrix by a vector, by hand

The operation you must burn into muscle:

**Matrix-vector multiplication.** Given a matrix `M` of shape (m, n)
and a vector `v` of length n, `M*v` is a vector of length m. The
i-th component of `M*v` is the dot product of row i of `M` with `v`.

That is the whole rule. Every row of `M` takes a dot product with
`v`. You get one number per row. Those numbers stack into the
output vector.

Let's do it by hand.

```
(define M-rows
  (list (list 1 2 3)
        (list 4 5 6)))

(define v (list 10 20 30))

(define (dot-list a b)
  (if (null? a)
      0
      (+ (* (car a) (car b))
         (dot-list (cdr a) (cdr b)))))

(define (matvec rows v)
  (map (lambda (row) (dot-list row v)) rows))

(display (matvec M-rows v))
;; => (140 320)
```

Check by eye:

- Row 0 dot v = 1*10 + 2*20 + 3*30 = 10 + 40 + 90 = 140.
- Row 1 dot v = 4*10 + 5*20 + 6*30 = 40 + 100 + 180 = 320.

Two rows in `M`, two numbers in the output. This is a function `M`
that turned a 3-vector into a 2-vector. That is what every
fully-connected layer does: shrink or grow the dimension of a vector
by multiplying by a matrix.

## Problem 3 — The same thing using Motoi's `map` and higher-order

Now the same operation, using `map` and a `vec/dot`. This is the
idiomatic Motoi form.

```
(define M
  (list (list 1 2 3))
        (list 4 5 6))))

(define v (list 10 20 30))

(define (matvec rows v)
  (map (lambda (row) (vec/dot row v)) rows))

(display (matvec M v))
;; => (140 320)
```

Notice that we stored `M` as a list of vectors, not as a `matrix/make`
object. That is deliberate — in the network code that follows, having
rows as vectors makes it obvious that the operation is a per-row dot
product. When we need `matrix/transpose` or `matrix/multiply` we will
use the object form. When we need the row-view, we use the list-view.
Same underlying numbers.

## Problem 4 — What a matrix DOES to a vector

Some matrices do recognizable geometric things. Let's do three.

### The identity matrix

```
(define I
  (list (list 1 0 0))
        (list 0 1 0))
        (list 0 0 1))))

(define v (list 7 8 9))

(display (map (lambda (row) (vec/dot row v)) I))
;; => (7 8 9)
```

The identity matrix does nothing. Row 0 has a 1 in position 0 and
zeros elsewhere, so its dot with `v` picks out `v[0]`. Same for the
other rows. Every neural network layer starts life very close to
the identity if its weights are small and random.

### A scaling matrix

```
(define scale-2x
  (list (list 2 0 0))
        (list 0 2 0))
        (list 0 0 2))))

(define v (list 3 4 5))

(display (map (lambda (row) (vec/dot row v)) scale-2x))
;; => (6 8 10)
```

Two on the diagonal means every component doubles. This is what
`vec/scale` does but written as a matrix. It is a matrix that
happens to be diagonal.

### A shear

```
(define shear
  (list (list 1 1 0))
        (list 0 1 0))
        (list 0 0 1))))

(define v (list 1 1 0))

(display (map (lambda (row) (vec/dot row v)) shear))
;; => (2 1 0)
```

The shear matrix took `[1, 1, 0]` and turned it into `[2, 1, 0]`. The
x-component picked up the y-component. This is a linear
transformation: it tilts the whole space in one direction.

Matrices are functions. Every fully-connected layer of every
network is exactly a matrix-vector multiplication followed by a
nonlinearity. Everything else in the layer is bookkeeping.

## Problem 5 — matrix-matrix multiplication

Once you have matrix-vector, matrix-matrix is easy: it is matrix-vector
applied column-by-column of the second matrix.

Motoi ships `matrix/multiply` for the fast path.

```
(define A
  (matrix/make (list (list 1 2)
                     (list 3 4))))

(define B
  (matrix/make (list (list 5 6)
                     (list 7 8))))

(display (matrix/multiply A B))
;; => a 2x2 matrix ((19 22) (43 50))
```

Verify: `(1*5 + 2*7) = 19`. `(1*6 + 2*8) = 22`. `(3*5 + 4*7) = 43`.
`(3*6 + 4*8) = 50`. Yes.

The shape rule for matrix multiplication: `(m, k) × (k, n) = (m, n)`.
The inner dimensions must agree — they get summed over. The outer
dimensions determine the result shape. This shape rule is the
constant background of ML programming: you spend more time getting
shapes right than doing anything else.

## Capstone — Two layers by hand

This is a preview of chapter 8. Build a two-layer network as two
matrix-vector multiplies. Ignore the missing nonlinearity for now
(the nonlinearity is chapter 7).

```
(define W1
  (list (list 0.1 0.2 0.3))
        (list 0.4 0.5 0.6))
        (list 0.7 0.8 0.9))
        (list 1.0 1.1 1.2))))
;; 4x3 — turns a 3-vector into a 4-vector

(define W2
  (list (list 0.1 0.2 0.3 0.4))
        (list 0.5 0.6 0.7 0.8))))
;; 2x4 — turns a 4-vector into a 2-vector

(define (matvec rows v)
  (map (lambda (r) (vec/dot r v)) rows))

(define x (list 1 2 3))

(define h (vec/make (matvec W1 x)))    ;; hidden vector, length 4
(define y (matvec W2 h))               ;; output vector, length 2

(display h)
;; => a 4-vector
(display y)
;; => a 2-vector
```

You just wrote a two-layer network. Two matrix multiplications turn
a 3-vector into a 2-vector, through a 4-dimensional hidden
representation. Miss the nonlinearity between them and the whole
thing collapses to one matrix (chapter 7 explains why); include the
nonlinearity and you can approximate any smooth function you want
(chapter 8 explains why).

## Why this matters

Every layer of a fully-connected network is a matrix-vector
multiplication. The transformer has fully-connected layers all over
the place — in the attention head, in the feed-forward block, in the
output projection. What you learned here IS the workhorse operation
of a language model. You are already partway there.

## What's next

Chapter 4 is a short chapter about function composition. Networks are
functions of functions of functions, so we need to be clear about
what that means and how Motoi's higher-order verbs let us compose
them.
")
